> came from:
>
>  a) Messing a lot with kernel modules and ddccontrol broke i2c sometimes.
>   
Yes surely.
>  c) I wasn't aware that /dev/i2c-* files are r-w for root only.
>   
Hum... http://ddccontrol.sourceforge.net/doc/0.4.2/ch02s04.html . Maybe
you should ask an udev rule for that, so the permissions are kept on reboot.
>  b) I hadn't identified the right device (here it is dev:/dev/i2c-4)
>
> Now I have no problem with the normal install in a fresh X-session when 
> running as root
>  # ddccontrol -r 0x72 -w 80 dev:/dev/i2c-4
> And after a quick
>  # chmod +s /usr/bin/ddccontrol
> a normal user can also run it [surely an entry in /etc/sudoers would be a 
> better idea].
>
>
> The i2c way is three times faster than pci, and ~0.60 sec/write is enough for 
> my fun. Anyway, if it were easy to implement someday, I'd suggest a kind of 
> "batch mode" that could scan-once write-many, like gddccontrol does: 
>
> $ ddccontrol -B dev:/dev/i2c-0
> Reading EDID and initializing DDC/CI
> Running in batch mode. Type "-r Control -w newvalue"  or path to file.
>  > -r 0x72 -w 80
>  > Writing 0x72, 0x50(80)...
>  > Control 0x72: +/80/160 C [Gamma - 1.8] 
>  > /home/common/resources/psychodelic_green2pink.ddcc
>  > Writing (...)
>  > _
>
> If this could be done, the election of pci or i2c wouldn't be important for 
> responsiveness.
>   
Yes... That sort of thing would be absolutely great... And it shouldn't
be really hard to do (if you look at ddccontrol main program, it is
really small), so, if somebody has the time to do this...

